<br>
I miss your reasoning here. I assume you're speaking about the Ten Commandments monument contraversy about being placed in the court house. I was speaking of the Ten Commandments monument in Casper city park which they are arguing gives way for Phelps hate monument to be placed in the same park. <br>
<br>
My opinion on that case actually differs, I don't believe they should have installed such a monument inside a courthouse. Sure much of our modern day laws represent the same laws presented in the Ten Commandments but Justice is supposed to be blind. Placing that monument in the courthouse represents a bias and that you may be judged unfairly based on a difference of background.<br>
<br>
The 'ten commandment' judge was another one who tried to pressure his religion onto others by his past experience. He had (what I assume was) christian prayer before the jurors on cases. He had the ten commandments hanging behind his bench, ran on a religious/ten commandment platform, the monument was the straw that broke the camels back.<br>
<br>
This is one area where church and state SHOULD be seperated. Someone commits adultery so you rule unfairly against them in divorce court leaving them not enough to even get by? You take one of your parents to civil court and the case gets thrown out or vise versa and they are ruled in favor of solely on the basis of 'Honor thy father and thy mother'?<br>
<br>
But having the monument up doesn't create more of an us and them enviroment any more than there already is. Its human nature to look at people as one of us or one of them. I think the psychological term they use for it is classing people into schemas(sp)? I think its Humanistic Psychology(?Whichever looks at psychology in natural/biological view point) claims it goes way back to recognising new people as friend or foe to accept or defend against them. What would create the us and them enviroment is that the judge wouldn't allow any monument from other religions to be put in the same space.<br>
<br>
<br>
